<div data-role="page" id="ref_prep_materials">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Materials</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>To play Mobile Frame Zero: Rapid Attack, you will need the following:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>One company of mobile frames per player consisting of 3 to 8 frames, depending on game type and number of players</li>
			<li>1 to 3 stations, depending on number of players</li>
			<li>Assorted terrain pieces used for cover</li>
			<li>An eight-unit game ruler</li>
			<li>A large number of dice, or a simulator (see below)</li>
			<li>A method to track doomsday and scoring (such as this app)</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Dice</h2>

		<p>If you use physical dice, (which is encouraged,) you will need a large amount. The number needed for a game varies; this list covers the worst-case scenario.</p>
		<ul>
			<li>4&#215; white d6</li>
			<li>1&#215; blue d6 per frame (max 25), plus 1</li>
			<li>1&#215; yellow d6 per frame (max 25)</li>
			<li>4&#215; green d6</li>
			<li>2&#215; green d8</li>
			<li>4&#215; red d6 (8 with split systems)</li>
			<li>8&#215; red d8</li>
			<li>14&#215; d6 of any color</li>
		</ul>

		<p>You can often play with less, but may need to improvise.</p>

		<div class="ref-note"><p>This app contains a simulator for dice rolling as well as tracking for game assets and status. These can be used in place of all physical dice and other physical bookkeeping.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_what-is_scale">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Frame Construction Requirements</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>Unless you have agreed beforehand, frames must fit inside a box that is 10 studs wide, 10 studs deep and 12 bricks tall. Frames must have removable systems to be able to represent damage. Using LEGO is expected but not required. There are no restrictions on what a frame should look like.</p>

		<p>It is generally accepted that MFZ:RA is played at "7p scale". This means an average human would be 7 LEGO plates tall. Build your frames with this in mind.</p>

		<p>If you want to play with an alternative scale, you will need to let all players know beforehand. Adjust your ruler, the play area, and the size and density of cover proportionally.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_prep_ruler">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Ruler, Units, and Measuring</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>A standard ruler is eight units long, with each unit 5 studs in length. Typically, 1&#215;4 click hinge bricks are used as they allow quickly lengthening or shortening the ruler to measure between objects, and routing the ruler around objects.</p>

		<p>All players may make measurements at any time.</p>

		<p>When measuring, use the closest part of each object. The hinge ruler can be placed between to see if it can touch both objects. The effect of using the hinge ruler is that one extra stud of length is added when measuring any distance. In the spirit of the game, this should be accepted as accurate as long as it is applied equally to all measurements.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_prep_area">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Game Area</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>Find or mark off a battlefield area that is circular or square, which measures between 4 and 6 ruler lengths at its widest.</p>

		<h2>Smaller &#38; larger fields</h2>
		<p>If you must use an area that is larger, expand your ruler units until the widest part of your play area fits within 4&#8211;6 rulers (of 8 units).</p>
		<p>To use a smaller area, reduce your ruler to 6 units.</p>
	</div>
</div>
