<div data-role="page" id="ref_prep_ranges">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Range Designations</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>Ranges map directly to the ruler and its units.</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Hand-to-hand: up to 1 unit</li>
			<li>Direct-fire: beyond 1 unit, but inside 1 ruler length</li>
			<li>Artillery: beyond 1 ruler length</li>
		</ul>

		<p>Ranges are exclusive. For example, artillery may only be used on targets beyond one ruler length. If there is a question about whether an object is in a given range, consider the object to be in range.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_prep_stations">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Stations</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>Stations represent valuable assets or locations, and are worth points for controlling. Stations do not count as cover and cannot be targeted or destroyed. A station:</p>

		<ul>
			<li>is distinct from cover and other terrain</li>
			<li>has a location to attach a flag or marker</li>
			<li>is no larger than 4&#215;4 studs wide</li>
		</ul>

		<p>Examples: cache of medical supplies, civilian scientist and family, research facility&#8217;s data storage drives, truck with a flat tire and a load of fresh peaches.</p>

		<div class="ref-hint"><p>If you want to use something with a larger base, discuss this with your group. Place it on the field like cover and other terrain during the setup phase and designate one or more 4&#215;4 stud areas that can be used as a station: a doorway for a building or a control terminal, perhaps. The rest of the piece is regular terrain or cover. Keep in mind that cover can be targeted and destroyed, while stations cannot.</p>
		<p>During deployment, any player may claim this as a station instead of placing one when they have opportunity to do so. If no player claims it, use it as normal terrain or cover.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_prep_terrain">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Terrain and Cover</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>Before the game, build several pieces of terrain. Terrain can be anything at all, but often cosists of walls, buildings, and vegetation. Imagination is encouraged.</p>

		<p>Any terrain on the battlefield is used as cover if it is at least 3 bricks high. Frames that have not been destroyed are also used as cover, regardless of ownership. Stations do not provide cover.</p>

		<p>Frames automatically use nearby cover when attacked. A target frame counts as being in cover to an attacking frame, if:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>it is within 1 unit range of the cover</li>
			<li>the cover is between target and attacker</li>
		</ul>
		<p>Ignore terrain pieces further away than 1 unit of the target, even if they are between the target and attacker.</p>

		<p>Terrain that is less than 3 bricks in height is no longer relevant. It cannot be used as cover and does not require frames to navigate around.</p>

		<div class="ref-hint"><p>Because terrain is damaged by removing a certain number of pieces, the number of pieces you use (at or above 3 bricks high) determine its durability. Terrain built from many small pieces will provide cover longer than terrain made from a few large pieces. Terrain which can absorb three hits and still be used for cover is generally considered very durable.</p></div>

		<div class="ref-note"><p>Advanced players often consider individual bricks for the purpose of cover instead of entire terrain pieces. This diverges from rules as written, but many players find it perferable.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_phases">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Phases</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>MFZ:RA is played across three phases: bidding, deployment and combat. You must construct your frame company (frames, systems, and stations) <strong>before</strong> you play. Keep your company hidden from other players.</p>

		<p>The game begins in the bidding phase, when each player's company is revealed to the other players. Based on the results of bidding, players begin deployment from different tactical positions. The final phase, combat, makes up the bulk of the game and determines the winner.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_bidding">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Bidding Phase</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>The game opens with the bidding phase.</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Compare the number of frames and systems within each company</li>
			<li>Determine each company&#8217;s PPA</li>
			<li>Determine each company&#8217;s starting score</li>
			<li>Resolve ties</li>
		</ul>

		<p>Smaller companies gain a points advantage to balance their lesser strength.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_ppa">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Assets, PPA, &amp; Score</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>Frames and stations are assets. <strong>Your score at any time is the number of assets you control multiplied by your points per asset (PPA) value.</strong> You are not eliminated from the game if you lose all of your frames; your stations still count toward your score unless they are captured. While extremely unlikely, it is technically possible to win with no frames remaining.</p><

		<p>Determine PPA only once, during the bidding phase. Every company starts with a value of 5. From here, apply the following modifiers:</p>
		<table class="ref-table">
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>Company has&#8230;</th>
					<th>Effect</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>most frames</td>
					<td>-1 PPA</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>most systems</td>
					<td>-1 PPA</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>least frames</td>
					<td>+1 PPA</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>least systems</td>
					<td>+1 PPA</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>
		<p>All players which meet each criteria adjust their scores.</p>
		<p>Calculate each player's score and multiply by the number of assets (frames and stations). As the game progresses the number of assets you control may change but your PPA value is never recalculated.</p>

		<div class="ref-calc"><p>Score = Assets &#215; PPA</p></div>

		<p>Your score determines your tactical position At the beginning of the game, and your initiative (the order in which players activate frames) throughout the game.</p>

		<h3>Tie for highest score</h3>
		<p>If two or more players tie for the highest score, a randomly chosen player must make a decision between these options:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>add a frame to their company</li>
			<li>remove a mobile frame from their company</li>
			<li>defer the choice to the next (randomly chosen) tied player</li>
		</ul>
		<p>Not all of these options may be available. A player must remain within the <a href="#ref_prep_game-size">normal minimum and maximum number of frames</a>, and may not defer the choice to someone who has already deferred.</p>

		<p>Restart the bidding phase: compare companies, determining new PPA and score.</p>

		<div class="ref-note"><p>This app will guide you through this process.</p></div>

		<h3>Tie for lowest score</h3>
		<p>If players tie for lowest score, a randomly chosen player must:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>place the point mobile frame</li>
			<li>go last in tactical order, until score changes</li>
		</ul>

		<p>If you plan to bid lower than the maximum number of frames, be sure to bring a spare mobile frame with you in case of a tie.</p>

		<div class="ref-note"><p>This app will handle this automatically.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_deploy_positions">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Deployment Phase &amp; Tactical Position</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>Once players have determined their PPA and initial scores, the deployment phase begins. First, determine your tactical position and initiative order. There are three tactical positions a player can be assigned: Defender, Point Attacker and Secondary Attacker. The score determines which position a player holds:</p>

		<table class="ref-table">
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>Player has&#8230;</th>
					<th>Tactical Position</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>&#8230; highest score</td>
					<td>Defender</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>&#8230; lowest score*</td>
					<td>Point Attacker</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>&#8230; neither</td>
					<td>Secondary Attacker</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>

		<p>*In the event of a tie, one randomly chosen player is the point attacker; others become secondary attackers. See <a href="#ref_play_ppa">Assets, PPA, &amp; Score</a></p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_deployment">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Deployment Process</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<div class="ref-note"><p>This app will guide you through deployment.</p></div>

		<p>Mark off your play area and place your terrain pieces on it. Any player can adjust the battlefield layout. Continue when all players are satsfied.</p>

		<h2>Defense Setup</h2>
		<p>The Defender places their stations wherever they like, each within one ruler length of at least one other station. Everything within one ruler around these stations is the <em>defensive perimeter</em>. Place two frames within this defensive perimeter. Leave at least one third of the battlefield outside the defensive perimeter, and at least one legal position for the Point Frame.</p>

		<h2>Point Frame</h2>
		<p>The Point Attacker places the point frame:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Out of cover to at least one of the Defender&#8217;s frames</li>
			<li>More than 1 ruler away from all Defender&#8217;s stations Outside the <em>defensive perimeter</em></li>
			<li>At exactly 1 ruler length from one of the Defender&#8217;s frames, in range for (but at the limit of) direct-fire</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Attackers&#8217; Frames</h2>
		<p>All offensive players alternate, descending by score, frame by frame, until all of their frames are on the field. Frames must be placed at least one ruler away from all of the Defender&#8217;s frames and stations.</p>

		<h2>Attackers&#8217; Stations</h2>
		<p>Attackers alternate again, descending by score, placing stations in a similar way. Stations may be placed anywhere on the field.</p>

		<h2>Defender&#8217;s Other Frames</h2>
		<p>The defender places any remaining frames. Frames placed outside the <em>defensive perimeter</em> must be in cover.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_combat">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Combat Phase</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>The combat phase is separated into rounds. The number of rounds played is decided by a doomsday clock, which continuously counts and players can accelerate. Doomsday is advanced at the end of each round, and the game is over when doomsday reaches zero. Remove all assigned defense and spot values before beginning a round.</p>

		<p>Within a round, every surviving frame is activated for one turn. The order in which frames are activated is decided by either <em>tactical order</em> or <em>combat order</em>. <em>Tactical order</em> is the default, but is overridden by <em>combat order</em> when a frame is targeted by an attack and reacts to incoming fire. The round ends when there are no frames left to activate.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_tactical-order">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Tactical Order</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p><em>Tactical order</em> is the normal method used to determine which frame activates next.</p>

		<p>The player with the highest score has the initiative, and chooses to activate a frame (take a turn) or pass. If the player passes, the player with the next lower score chooses to activate or pass, and so on. If all players with lower scores have activated all of their frames, a player may not pass and must activate a frame. A player automatically passes if all of his/her own frames have been activated.</p>

		<p>If a frame is attacked that has not yet activated this round, switch to <em>combat order</em>. Otherwise, each time a turn is resolved, the choice to activate returns to the player with the highest score.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_combat-order">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Combat Order</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p><em>Combat order</em> is used when a frame is coming under attack that has not yet activated this round. Otherwise, use <em>tacitcal order</em>. The defending frame is only activated if it actually needs to assign a defense value: the attacker is in range and has assigned an attack value.</p>

		<p>In <em>combat order</em>, the defender begins a turn before the attacker&#8217;s turn is finished:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><em>Attacker</em> takes a turn normally up until they are in range for an attack and have assigned an attack value</li>
			<li><em>Defender</em> names a target, rolls dice, and assigns a defense value</li>
			<li><em>Attacker</em> finishes turn (movement and spotting are possible)</li>
			<li><em>Defender</em> continues his/her turn</li>
		</ul>
		<p>In this process, the defending frame is activated. Once the attacker&#8217;s turn is completed, the defender continues its turn normally, including movement, attacks, and spotting. If this frame chooses to make an attack, it may become an attacker and need to pause its turn again for the new defender. This can create a chain of activations that carries through many players and frames. When a frame does not attack a frame that is not yet activated, return to tactical order.</p>

		<p>A frame that is destroyed does not get to continue its turn.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_capture-stations">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Capturing &#38; contested stations</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>A station is an asset. Players control their own stations when they are deployed, and can capture control of other stations on the field. Capturing stations increases a player&#8217;s score</p>

		<p>Update scores whenever a station is gained or lost, as this may lead to changes in <em>tactical order</em>.</p>

		<h2>Capturing stations</h2>

		<p>At any time and for any reason:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>You gain control of a station when you have a frame within 1 unit of the station <strong>and</strong> no other players have a frame within 1 unit of that station.</li>
			<li>You lose control of a station when any other player has a frame within 1 unit of the station <strong>and</strong> you do not have a frame within 1 unit of the station.</li>
		</ul>

		<p>Otherwise, stations do not change hands&#8212;even if a player&#8217;s frames are destroyed. You must be stopped to capture or hold a station; you cannot capture a station by passing near it during your movement action.</p>

		<h2>Contested stations</h2>

		<p>In a game with three or more players, it&#8217;s possible for a station to be lost without also being captured. This happens when:</p>
		<ol>
			<li>A player has a frame within 1 unit of a station he/she controls</li>
			<li>Two or more opponents move a frame within the 1-unit capture range</li>
			<li>The controlling player&#8217;s frame moves away or is destroyed</li>
		</ol>

		<p>This results in immediate loss of control of the station. However, control cannot be claimed by either opponent. The station can only be controlled again when only one company has frames within capture range.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_doomsday">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Doomsday</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>The length of the game is determines by the Doomsday Clock. After each round, Doomsday counts down automatically and each player may choose to accelerate it.</p>

		<p>The Doomsday Clock starts at 11. When a round ends, count down Doomsday by one. Then, each player in order from highest to lowest score, is given an opportunity to count down the clock by an additional point. When Doomsday reaches zero, the game ends.</p>

		<p>If you lose all of your frames, you may still count down the doomsday clock.</p>

		<p>The player with the highest score wins. In the event of a tie, the game does not go to overtime or use any secondary method to resolve them&#8212;it simply ends in a tie.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_play_judgment">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Principled Judgment Calls</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>If a situation is unclear, favor the outcome intended by the player taking the action. In detail, when a measurement is close:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Attack &amp; Spot: consider the target to be within the attacker&#8217;s/spotter&#8217;s desired range.</li>
			<li>Moving: allow the frame to move to that position</li>
			<li>Defense: consider the defender to be in cover (the defender is taking the action here)</li>
		</ul>

	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_frame_turn-sequence">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Turn Sequence</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>When a frame is activates, its turn follows a given sequence:</p>
		<ol>
			<li><a href="#ref_frame_target">Designate a Target</a></li>
			<li><a href="#ref_frame_roll-dice">Roll Dice</a></li>
			<li><a href="#ref_frame_defense">Assign Defense</a></li>
			<li><a href="#ref_frame_moving">Move</a> and <a href="#ref_frame_attacking">Attack</a> (in either order)</li>
			<li><a href="#ref_frame_spotting">Spot</a></li>
		</ol>

		<p>Complete each step before moving on to the next. A frame&#8217;s activation may pause as a result of combat, and resumes where it left off.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_frame_target">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true">
		<h1>Designate a Target</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>Name a target for this frame&#8217;s attack. You may target an opponent frame, a piece of terrain, or nothing at all. You may not target a station or any frame you own.</p>
		<p>You must also declare what range you will make the attack from. You do not need to be within that range when you declare the attack, but you must move into it before you can begin attacking. Not all frames are capable of attacking at all ranges. Frames may always attack at hand-to-hand range.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_frame_roll-dice">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Roll Dice</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>Determine which dice you have available to roll based on your declared attack range, current systems, frame damage, and any SSRs you choose to use. See <a href="#ref_prep_frame-systems">Frame Capabilities (Systems, SSR, Sprinting)</a>. You may only roll dice for weapon systems in the range you declared. For example, you may not roll for an artillery system if you declared an attack at hand-to-hand range.</p>

		<p>Roll dice for your frame activation all at once. You will assign values from this result in later steps of your activation in order to take actions: defend, attack, move, spot.</p>

		<ul>
			<li>You may only take an action if you assign a die to it</li>
			<li>You may only assign one die for each action</li>
			<li>You may not assign a die to more than one action</li>
			<li>You may only assign a white die or a die of the correct type (See <a href="#ref_prep_dice">Dice Assignments</a>)</li>
		</ul>

		<p>Your roll is public information. You choose to make assignments in later steps, after you see the result of your roll. There is no requirement to assign any dice or take any action. You may not have enough dice available to take every action. Set used dice aside from the pool as you assign them. Unused dice are discarded at the end of your turn.</p>

		<p>If you added any dice to your pool because you chose to use one or more SSRs, discard the rocket from your frame now. Dice added by SSRs are not considered differently from any other red dice in the pool.</p>

		<div class="ref-note">
			<p>See <a href="#ref_quick_example-assignment">Example Dice Assignment</a></p>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_frame_defense">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Assign Defense</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>If you choose to defend, assign a blue or white die from your pool as your defensive value. This defensive value is never changed or removed until the entire round is over. Place a blue die on the field next to this frame with the value turned upward to help everyone remember this. If you choose not to defend, your defensive value becomes zero. You will not be able to place a die on the table in this case, so use a different kind of marker if you need to. The frame is not given another opportunity to assign defense until the next round.</p>

		<p>If you are currently under attack, pause your activation here until the attacking frame&#8217;s turn has completed.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_frame_moving">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Move</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>If you choose to move, assign a green or white die from your pool as your movement value. You may move any distance not exceeding this number in ruler units.</p>

		<p>If you did not roll a green die, you must navigate around any object providing cover (terrain and frames; see <a href="#ref_prep_terrain">Terrain and Cover</a>). This will limit the effective distance you can travel.</p>

		<p>If you rolled a green die, you may ignore cover while moving and measure directly to your desired endpoint. Rolling a green die also allows you to stand on top of cover. Standing on frames is permitted. Frames do not prohibit others them from moving. When a lower frame moves, keep the upper frame in the same X/Y location.</p>

		<div class="ref-reminder"><p>Movement systems each provide a green die that unlocks these capabilities. Sprinting also provides a green die. See <a href="#ref_prep_frame-systems">Frame Capabilities (Systems, SSR, Sprinting)</a>.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_frame_attacking">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Attack</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>You may only attack the target you previously designated, but you are not required to. Your attack must be made from the declared range; if you are not within that range you are unable to attack. (If you have not yet used your movement action, consider doing so to position yourself within your desired range.) Do not consider line of sight when making an attack. If you are within range and you choose to attack, assign a red or white die from your pool as your attack value.</p>

		<p>You only attack when you assign a value from your pool. You cannot assign a value of zero. You cannot abort an attack once assigned.</p>

		<p>If you attack a frame that has already activated or if you attack cover, resolve the attack now. Attacking a frame that has not yet activated will cause it to activate next. (See <a href="#ref_play_combat-order">Combat Order</a>.) Pause your turn here until the target frame has a defense value, then resolve the attack. (See <a href="#ref_frame_resolve-attacks">Resolve Attacks</a>.)</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_frame_spotting">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Spot</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>Any frame may spot another frame within one ruler length that is out of cover, but your frame may be capable of spotting frames in cover and frames anywhere on the field. Take a look at the field and your <a href="#ref_prep_frame-systems">Frame Capabilities</a> to determine if you are capable of spotting. If you are able and you choose to spot, assign a yellow or white die from your pool as your spot value. Place a yellow die on the field next to the spotted frame with the value turned upward to help everyone remember this.</p>

		<p>Only opponent frames may be spotted. Terrain and stations cannot be spooted. The frame you spot does not need to be the same frame you attacked. You do not need to declare your spot beforehand. A frame may not have multiple spot values. If the frame you wish to spot already has a spot value, you may replace it if the new value is greater.</p>

		<p>Spotting is always the last step in your activation; you may not spot before you attack.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_frame_resolve-attacks">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Resolving Attacks</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<h2>Get Defense and Spot Values</h2>
		<p>First, make sure your target has a defense value. A frame that has not yet activated this round does so now. A frame that has activated but chooses not to defend has a value of zero. The defense value of terrain is always zero.</p>

		<p>Next, if the target has been spotted, choose whether to add the spot value to your attack. If you do, remove the spot marker die from the field. Anyone can use a spot placed by anyone else. Terrain cannot be spotted.</p>

		<div class="ref-note"><p>The target frame&#8217;s spot value is removed from the field, but the target frame&#8217;s defense value remains.</p></div>

		<h2>Calculate and Assemble Damage Pool</h2>
		<p>Next, determine how many damage dice you will roll. Damage dice are always D6, rolled and consulted immediately, then discarded. Use any dice that are available regardless of color. (Or, use this app&#8217;s simulator.) Pick up the number of dice equal to your assigned attack value. If you choose to use a target&#8217;s spot, add the number of dice equal to that value. Finally, subtract a number of dice equal to the defense value of the target.</p>

		<div class="ref-calc"><p>Damage Dice = Attack + Spot - Defense</p></div>

		<p>If you do not have any dice left after subtracting defense, the attack misses and is now resolved. Otherwise, roll the damage pool now. Do this separately from any frame activation dice so they do not mingle and become confused.</p>

		<h2>Determine Current Situation</h2>

		<p>Check whether the target is in cover. (See <a href="#ref_prep_terrain">Terrain and Cover</a>.) Terrain is never considered to be in cover. How you apply damage depends on the target type, range, and value of each damage die.</p>

		<table class="ref-table">
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>Target Type</th>
					<th>Range</th>
					<th>Covered by</th>
					<th>Hits Cover</th>
					<th>Hits Target</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td rowspan="4">Frame</td>
					<td rowspan="3">Direct-fire or artillery</td>
					<td>Terrain</td>
					<td>4 &amp; 5</td>
					<td>6</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Frame</td>
					<td>5*</td>
					<td>6</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>None</td>
					<td>-</td>
					<td>5 &amp; 6</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Hand-to-hand</td>
					<td>N/A</td>
					<td>-</td>
					<td>4, 5 &amp; 6</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Terrain</td>
					<td>Any</td>
					<td>N/A</td>
					<td>-</td>
					<td>4, 5 &amp; 6</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>

		<p>*A frame with two defensive systems is not hit.</p>

		<p>See <a href="#ref_quick_hit-chart">Hit Chart</a> for a graphic representation.</p>

		<p>Resolve each damage die one at a time, beginning with the lowest value and working upward. If cover is destroyed, apply the remaining damage dice per the new situation.</p>

		<h2>Applying Hits</h2>

		<p>When a hit connects, take any removed bricks from terrain, systems, or frames, and drop them onto the battlefield.</p>

		<h3>Terrain</h3>
		<p>For each hit to terrain, remove 6 bricks from it. The attacker chooses which to remove, but may not remove bricks that have others stacked on top of them.</p>

		<h3>Frame</h3>
		<p>If the target frame is currently within one unit of a station it controls, the defender may choose to move the frame directly away from the station until it is immediately outside the range to hold the station (1 unit) instead of taking a hit. This can only be done once per attack.</p>

		<p>For each hit to a frame, remove one system. This system is destroyed and does not provide any benefits in future rounds.	However, if the target frame is in the middle of its activation when it is hit, it may still use the destroyed system for this round (as long as the entire frame is not destroyed).</p>

		<p>If a frame has no systems, the frame itself is damaged. This causes the loss of one of its white dice for all future rolls.</p>

		<p>If both white dice are lost, the frame is destroyed. It no longer counts as an asset for its owner and cannot be activated again. Recalculate the score.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_quick_example-assignment">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Example Dice Assignment</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>A frame with the loadout of
		<span class="sys-display"><span data-sys="w">W</span><span data-sys="w">W</span><span data-sys="rh">Rd</span><span data-sys="b">B</span><span data-sys="g">G</span></span> rolls:</p>
		<ul class="roll-display "><li data-die="w6" data-type="w">3</li><li data-die="w6" data-type="w">5</li><li data-die="r6" data-type="r">3</li><li data-die="r6" data-type="r">5</li><li data-die="b6" data-type="b">4</li><li data-die="g6" data-type="g">2</li></ul>

		<p>First, the player must assign defense. The player can choose either the blue <span data-die="b6" data-type="b">4</span> or one of the whites <span data-die="w6" data-type="w">3</span><span data-die="w6" data-type="w">5</span>. The player chooses the <span data-die="b6" data-type="b">4</span>. It is assigned to defense and placed on the table near the frame.</p>

		<p>Next, the player can choose to attack or move. The player chooses to move first, and must choose a die for its movement: the green <span data-die="g6" data-type="g">2</span> or one of the whites <span data-die="w6" data-type="w">3</span><span data-die="w6" data-type="w">5</span>. The player needs to move to get in range of its target, and chooses the <span data-die="w6" data-type="w">5</span>. It can now move up to 5 ruler units. The <span data-die="w6" data-type="w">5</span> has been assigned and cannot be used for additional actions. The green <span data-die="g6" data-type="g">2</span> can be discarded now because it is only usable for movement.</p>

		<p>The player now makes an attack and can choose red <span data-die="r6" data-type="r">3</span> or <span data-die="r6" data-type="r">5</span>, or white <span data-die="w6" data-type="w">3</span>. The player chooses <span data-die="r6" data-type="r">5</span>. The red <span data-die="r6" data-type="r">3</span> can be discarded.</p>

		<p>Finally, the player may choose a spot. The frame does not have a spot (yellow) system, so only the white <span data-die="w6" data-type="w">3</span> is available to be assigned. The player is not required to use it.</p>

		<p>The turn is over, and any remaining dice are now discarded.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_quick_example-attack">
