<div data-role="page" id="ref_optional_split-range">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Split-Range Weapons</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<div class="ref-note"><p>All players must agree which advanced rules will be used before play begins, and ideally before creating a company. Advanced rules are enabled for this app through the settings from the main page.</p></div>

		<p>A weapon system may be split between two ranges. For the purpose of frame construction, a split-range system counts as two half-systems, one of each type. You still may not exceed more than two total systems of each type.</p>
		<p>Each half of the split-range system provides one red d6 in the appropriate range. If you use any split-range systems, you cannot gain the red d8 for having a second full system.</p>
		<p>When a split-range system is destroyed, you lose the entire system.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_optional_elevation">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Elevation &amp; Falling Damage</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<div class="ref-note"><p>All players must agree which advanced rules will be used before play begins, and ideally before creating a company. Advanced rules are enabled for this app through the settings from the main page.</p></div>

		<p>A frame that is at least 6 bricks higher than another frame is at elevation with respect to it. A frame at elevation uses the structure it is standing on as cover. Frames below it can only be covered by an object directly above them, such as a roof.</p>

		<p>Frames must use movement to climb or descend structures. Terrain can be built with natural methods to climb or descend such as ramps, stairs, or ladders. Frames that do not roll green must use these methods. A frame rolling green may always climb. To use a ladder or "free-climb" a structure, one movement unit can be used for 6 bricks of height.</p>

		<p>When a structure is hit, it may be destroyed or become unstable. Use your best judgement on this, as it will often be difficult to make a clear call. Be generous to the defender. If you decide that a frame has fallen, roll one damage die for every 3 bricks height of the fall. The frame received damage on 4, 5, and 6.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_optional_hazardous">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Hazardous Areas</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<div class="ref-note"><p>All players must agree which advanced rules will be used before play begins, and ideally before creating a company. Advanced rules are enabled for this app through the settings from the main page.</p></div>

		<p>When you set up the field, designate areas as hazardous. Indicate this in some meaningful way on the field. A differently colored or textured ground surface is common, but you can also use a determined radius from designated terrain. When you actiavte a frame that is inside a hazard area, you must reduce your dice pool by one white die.</p>

		<p>During company construction, you may choose an environmental system as part of any frame&#8217;s loadout. This is a system like any other and counts for all purposes such as loadout maximums, scoring, and damage. If a frame has an environmental system when it activates, it is not affected by a hazard when rolling (does not lose a white die).</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_optional_per-frame-initiative">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Per-frame initiative</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<div class="ref-note"><p>All players must agree which advanced rules will be used before play begins, and ideally before creating a company. Advanced rules are enabled for this app through the settings from the main page.</p></div>

		<p>At the beginning of each round, roll a d20 for each frame. For any frame with less than four systems, roll an additional d20. Place these next to the frame.</p>

		<p>During tactical order, find the frame with the lowest value. This frame activates now. If a frame has two dice, its owner chooses which value to use when the lower number comes up. Resolve ties with a roll-off.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_optional_drop-white">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Dropping Whites for Damage</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<div class="ref-note"><p>All players must agree which advanced rules will be used before play begins, and ideally before creating a company. Advanced rules are enabled for this app through the settings from the main page.</p></div>

		<p>When you take damage, you may choose to assign it to your frame instead of one of its systems. Drop a white die from the frame&#8217;s dice pool for all future activations. You can only do this if the frame is not yet damaged; a second hit to a frame will destroy it.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_optional_jettison">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Jettisoning Systems</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<div class="ref-note"><p>All players must agree which advanced rules will be used before play begins, and ideally before creating a company. Advanced rules are enabled for this app through the settings from the main page.</p></div>

		<p>Before you roll your dice, you may remove systems from your own frame. Lay them on the field as if destroyed in battle; these cannot be picked up and used again. This has the effect of damaging your frame but may add the Green d8 to the dicepool when you roll. You may not jettison Whites.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div data-role="page" id="ref_other_demo">
	<div data-role="header" data-add-back-btn="true" data-position="fixed" data-tap-toggle="false">
		<h1>Demo games</h1>
	</div>
	<div role="main" class="ui-content">
		<p>These simplified rules are suggested to help quickly introduce new players. You may find them useful at conventions or any time the game is demonstrated. If you&#8217;re quick with the rules, this is a 15- or 20-minute demo for 3 players, maybe a 30-minute demo for 5.</p>

		<p>Place one station in the middle of the field. Provide each player with one soldier frame and one alternate, either a hand-to-hand or artillery variant. Frames are placed by the demo organizer, roughly following these guidelines:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>some in cover, some out of cover</li>
			<li>in roughly equilateral triangles whose sides are the length of direct fire range&#8212;some of the triangles include the objective as a corner point, some don't</li>
			<li>each player has a frame at 5&#8211;6 units away from the station, but nobody has one closer</li>
		</ul>

		<p>The idea is to put every frame at a moment of decision, and an easy way to do it is to put them just within direct-fire range from an enemy or a goal.</p>

		<p>All assets are worth 5 points. Tell players: &#8220;in the full game, things are worth different points to different players, but here, everything&#8217;s worth 5 points. You each have 2 frames so you each have 10 points. If you lose a frame, you lose 5 points. If you capture the station, you gain 5 points.&#8221;</p>

		<p>Set the doomsday clock to 5. Expect to play 2 rounds. &#8220;When the doomsday clock hits zero, whoever has the most points wins.&#8221;</p>

		<p>&#8220;In the full game, initiative depends on how many points you have, and maybe we&#8217;ll see that next turn. Since everybody&#8217;s equal now, we&#8217;ll just start on my left and go around.&#8221;</p>

		If somebody&#8217;s not getting the rules, I try to just talk them clearly through the decisions their dice are asking them to make. &#8220;First choose your target. Now gather your dice: you get [these]. Roll &#8216;em! Okay, now you need a defense value. Choose a blue or a white. Perfect. Now, do you want to move first, then attack, or attack first, then move? Great. Here&#8217;s what we do&#8230;&#8221;</p>

		<div class="ref-note"><p>Demo games are supported by this app.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
